    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When you pay more than the minimum payment, the extra amount you pay goes directly towards reducing the principal balance. This is because the interest is calculated based on the outstanding balance, and when you pay more than the minimum, you're reducing the balance, which in turn reduces the interest.\n\nHowever, there is a catch. Many student loans have a feature called \"interest capitalization\" or \"interest carryover,\" which can make it seem like the interest is still high even when you're paying extra. This means that if you pay more than the minimum, the interest is still calculated on the original balance, and the excess amount you paid is simply added to the principal.\n\nFor example, let's say you have a balance of $10,000 and you pay $500 in interest for the month. If you pay $1,000 in total (the minimum payment plus the extra $500), the interest capitalization feature would mean that:\n\n* The interest for the month is still $450 (on the original balance of $10,000)\n* The excess $500 you paid is added to the principal, reducing the balance to $9,500\n\nIn this case, the interest for the next month would be calculated on the new balance of $",
